<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">
Only known from the type locality (
<bibRefCitation author="Holthuis, LB" journalOrPublisher="Problemi Attuali di Scienza e di Cultura, Quaderni Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" pagination="173 - 195" publicationUrl="https://decapoda.nhm.org/references/pdfpick.html?id=25798&amp;pdfroot=https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs" refId="B66" refString="Holthuis, LB, 1977. Cave Shrimps (Crustacea, Decapoda, Natantia) from Mexico. In: Subterranean Fauna of Mexico, Part III. Problemi Attuali di Scienza e di Cultura, Quaderni Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 173 - 195, https://decapoda.nhm.org/references/pdfpick.html?id=25798&amp;pdfroot=https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs" title="Cave Shrimps (Crustacea, Decapoda, Natantia) from Mexico. In: Subterranean Fauna of Mexico, Part III." url="https://decapoda.nhm.org/references/pdfpick.html?id=25798&amp;pdfroot=https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs" volume="171" year="1977">Holthuis 1977</bibRefCitation>
; present paper).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="life cycle">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Life cycle.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">
Exclusive of inland waters, therefore independent of brackish waters to complete its life cycle. The eggs are few and large: 1.9-2.5 mm (
<bibRefCitation author="Villalobos Hiriart, JL" journalOrPublisher="San Diego State University, San Diego" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" publicationUrl="https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs/26690/26690.pdf" refId="B174" refString="Villalobos Hiriart, JL, Nates Rodriguez, JC, Cantu Diaz Barriga, A, 1989. https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs/26690/26690.pdf" url="https://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs/26690/26690.pdf" year="1989">Villalobos Hiriart et al. 1989</bibRefCitation>
). Its larval development is not known but given the characteristics of the eggs, it should be abbreviated, following the same pattern of congeners inhabiting continental waters (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/156854088X00384" author="Magalhaes, C" journalOrPublisher="Crustaceana" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" pagination="279 - 292" refId="B87" refString="Magalhaes, C, Walker, I, 1988. Larval development and ecological distribution of Central Amazonian palaemonid shrimps (Decapoda: Caridea). Crustaceana 55 (3): 279 - 292, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/156854088X00384" title="Larval development and ecological distribution of Central Amazonian palaemonid shrimps (Decapoda: Caridea)." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/156854088X00384" volume="55" year="1988">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Magalhães">Magalhaes</normalizedToken>
and Walker 1988
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/193724095X00631" author="Pereira, GA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Crustacean Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" pagination="117 - 133" refId="B128" refString="Pereira, GA, Garcia, DJV, 1995. Larval development of Macrobrachuym reyesi Pereira (Decapoda: Palaemonidae), with a discussion on the origin of abbreviated development in palaemonids. Journal of Crustacean Biology 15 (1): 117 - 133, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/193724095X00631" title="Larval development of Macrobrachuym reyesi Pereira (Decapoda: Palaemonidae), with a discussion on the origin of abbreviated development in palaemonids." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/193724095X00631" volume="15" year="1995">
Pereira and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="García">Garcia</normalizedToken>
1995
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">
Among the epigean forms of this group of species with abbreviated development and without hepatic spine, 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. perspicax" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perspicax">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">M. perspicax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. candango" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candango">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">M. candango</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nom. nov., comb. nov. and 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. alevillalobosi" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alevillalobosi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">M. alevillalobosi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nom. nov., comb. nov. by the total length of the body, and by the similar form and size of the second pereiopod and the proportion of its articles (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphological comparison of key characters for the species previously included in the genus Cryphiops Dana, 1852." pageId="0" pageNumber="155">2</tableCitation>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. perspicax" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perspicax">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">M. perspicax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. are generally smaller (31.1-43.3 mm) than those of the other two species; the second pereiopods are shorter, do not present heterochely like 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="M. candango" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candango">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">M. candango</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nom. nov., comb. nov. and the chelae are slender, the palm is 3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as high, and the dactylus is slightly shorter.
</paragraph>
